The paper deals with the problem of computing the Fourier Transform of a signal with a small number of dominant frequencies using a small number of samples. This problem is related to signal processing and information theory, which suggests that cs.IT (Information Theory) is a likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a new technique for analyzing noisy hashing schemes, which is related to data structures and algorithms, indicating that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is another possible sub-category. The paper also mentions model-based Sparse FFT, which is related to machine learning and signal processing, suggesting that cs.SI (Machine Learning) is a possible sub-category. The paper also discusses the computational complexity of the problem, which is related to computational geometry and numerical analysis, indicating that cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) are also possible sub-categories.
